column17: AK - Some businesses allowed to operate at minimum basic operations despite order to close non-essential businesses

column18: AZ- casinos temp closed but the decision was left up to sovereing tribal nations. Not a statewide mandate

column17: CA - Restaurants and non-essential businesses closed with stay-at-home order

column18: CO- local "variances" allowed certain county re-openings no statewide opening order as of 11/30/2020
CT- governor negotiated with tribal casinos for their closing and reopening of tribal casinos. The only non-tribal gaming is OTB.

column15: DE - Day cares only remained open for children of essential workers

column17: GA - Governor ordered non-essential businesses to operate at minimum basic operations, but did not order them to close
column18: GA- All casinos in the state are on boats/cruises

column15: IL - Day cares only remained open for children of essential workers

column18: IN- no closing/opening mandate EO's but press releases confirmed these dates.

column15: IA - Governor recommended schools close 5/15; Ordered schools to close 4/2
column17: IA - Order to close non-essential businesses only mentions retail/personal care businesses
KS - Statewide stay-at-home order went into effect 3/30/20 and closed all non-essential businesses

column15: ME - Order to close schools came after schools had already voluntarily closed statewide

column18: MA- 3/14 Massachusetts Gaming Commission voted unanimously to temporarily suspend operation at the state’s three casino properties, including Encore Boston Harbor, MGM Springfield and Plainridge Park Casino. 3/24 EO also included language suspending operations for Casino's in MA.

column16: MN - 3/16 EO allowed veterans homes to implement CMS guidelines from 3/13; no formal EOs regarding closure of nursing homes outside of this category

column17: MS - 10 people or less allowed at bars

column15: MO - Order to close schools came after most schools had already closed
NE - Schools closed in some counties 3/23; order to close schools extended to all counties 4/3
column17: NE - Non-essential retail was not ordered to be closed but personal care services like nail salons and hairdressers were; 4/3 order set rules for how gyms could remain open (but never closed gyms) and capped gatherings in indoor theaters at 10 persons
NJ - Bars not technically closed, but most in person alcohol sales prohibited

column18: NM- order excludes casinos on tribal land.
NC- Tribal Casinos only. Chose to close March 18th. No state orders enforcing this decision though the 3/25/2020 EO including closing of gaming venues, it did not apply to tribal governemnts.

column17: ND - Started closing non-essential businesses statewide on 3/20 but did not release EO until 3/27, which listed the dates of all closures that had happened until that point

column18: OH- Governor/State Casino Control Commission told casinos they had to comply with no "mass gathering rules," not that they had to shut down, but casinos chose to shut down from March until June on their own.

column17: OR - Closed non-essential retail 3/24/2020, but did not mandate non-retail closures
PA - Bar closures began in some counties on 3/16
column18: PA- The PA gaming control board closed all casinos in the state on 3/17/2020 ahead of the EO closing non-essential buisnesses in the state.

column15: RI - Order to close schools came after schools had already closed statewide
column17: RI - Order to close non-essential businesses only applied to retail closures
SC - Order to close non-essential businesses mostly applied to retail, entertainment venues & athletic facilities
column18: SC- All casinos in the state are on boats/cruises

column17: SD - EO states that non-essential businesses "should" be open only to maximum of 10 people but does not specify enforcement of this
column18: SD- No buisness was ever required to close in SD.

column15: TN - Schools recommended to close by governor, but all school districts complied

column16: UT - State issued a health order for nursing homes to follow guidance from CMS on 3/19; 4/1 order suggested limiting visits to nursing homes and long term facilities
column17: UT - 3/27 order never explicitly closed gyms and theaters but did say 'do not travel to...'; UT later issued orders explicitly opening these businesses

If closure announced on weekend, first week day closed is listed. If closure announced in evening, considered to apply to next day. Some states only applied order to public schools.
column5: If closure announced in evening, considered to apply to next day. If closure announced on weekend, first week day closed is listed.

column4: If not specified in order, the date of closure was the first school day after a closure order was signed
